results.name: a(1)=1, a(2)=2, a(3)=3; for n > 3, a(n) is the smallest positive integer which does not occur earlier in the sequence and which is not coprime to a(n-2).
comment: Conjecture: this is a permutation of the positive integers, cf. A256618. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 05 2015
link: N. J. A. Sloane, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..20632
maple: # From _N. J. A. Sloane_, Apr 04 2015: A121217 gcd(A[n],A[n-2])>1 A=seq, for B see the COMMENTS
N:= 60: # to get a(1) to a(n) where a(n+1) is the first term > N
for n from 1 to 3 do A[n]:= n: od:
for k from 4 to N do
if B[k] = 0 and igcd(k, A[n-2]) > 1 then
if k > N then break fi
mathematica: a = Range@ 3; Do[k = 4; While[Or[MemberQ[a, k], CoprimeQ[a[[i - 2]], k]], k++]; AppendTo[a, k], {i, 4, 72}]; a (* _Michael De Vlieger_, Aug 19 2017 *)
program: f u v xs = g xs where
g (w:ws) = if gcd w u > 1 then w : f v w (delete w xs) else g ws
